    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-08-22T15:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-08-22T15:30:00-05:00" n="234"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d234">
                <head>234. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in the Congo<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d234fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1964–66, POL 23–9 THE
                        CONGO. Confidential; Immediate. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_OJL_1"
                            >O’Sullivan</persName>; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_FJW_1"
                            >Fredericks</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_THJ_1">Tasca</persName>,
                        and Grant; and approved by <persName corresp="#p_OJL_1"
                            >O’Sullivan</persName>. Repeated to Brussels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-08-22T16:30:00-04:00">August 22, 1964, 4:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>418. Stan Consular Staff. There follow some suggestions which Emb should explore
                    and comment upon.</p>
                <p>1. We need counter hostages. Can <gloss target="#t_GOC_1">GOC</gloss> (perhaps
                        <persName corresp="#p_NVI_1">Nendaka</persName>) put under protective
                    surveillance any relatives of rebel leaders such as <persName corresp="#p_ONI_1"
                        >Olenga</persName> (if he is still alive) <persName corresp="#p_SGE_1"
                        >Soumialot</persName>, or any others whom Emb believes may be influential
                    there. It might be possible grab some important rebel leaders in <gloss
                        target="#t_Leo_1">Leo</gloss> or Bukavu for this purpose.</p>
                <pb facs="0374" n="341" xml:id="pg_341"/>
                <p>2. Explore with Yugoslav Mission <gloss target="#t_Leo_1">Leo</gloss> whether it
                    has any way of reaching rebels and would it be willing act as intermediary for
                    purpose extricating <persName corresp="#p_HMP_1">Hoyt</persName> and staff.</p>
                <p>3. Indian and Greek missions may have connections with their respective
                    communities in Stan. There is no reason to believe that rebels are immune to
                    carrots that attract other Congolese. In this connection has Alhadeff any
                    ideas?</p>
                <p>4. We have considered asking <persName corresp="#p_NKW_1">Nkrumah</persName> to
                    act as intermediary. This idea temporarily held in abeyance due 1) possibility
                    Quashie may be PNGed and 2) probability that he would try expand his role from
                    extrication of <persName corresp="#p_HMP_1">Hoyt</persName> to full scale
                    mediation between <gloss target="#t_GOC_1">GOC</gloss> and rebels.</p>
                <p>We are going to approach Aboud (Sudan) (see separate tel)<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d234fn2">Not identified.</note> in whose case these drawbacks are
                    not present.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RDE_1">Rusk</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
